WEBVTT

00:02.250 --> 00:07.850
But I think it was also the singing and setting up of 
the bonfire, all of that was just such a treat

00:10.270 --> 00:14.070
because never had she experienced something like 
that before. All right, that first year, you

00:14.590 --> 00:19.790
didn't encounter any hazing then. No. You weren't 
a fish in the normal sense of the word. No, I didn't,

00:25.710 --> 00:30.590
but I think I began to hear about, I knew I had some 
freshmen, and I knew I had friends of mine that were

00:30.570 --> 00:34.090
fish. A lot of my classmates from Bryan did not join 
the Corps, though I saw them occasionally. But I

00:42.410 --> 00:47.430
guess those schoolmates of mine that ended up 
going, I remember them, and I saw them in their

00:48.210 --> 00:54.110
uniform and short hair and kind of in their state of 
shock at first. And I remember them. I guess the

01:00.570 --> 01:05.670
other thing that I remember quite vividly was 
during the bonfire, during the cutting of the

01:05.650 --> 01:10.830
bonfire, how many of them were just dozing off in 
class. And so it was those kinds of experiences

01:10.810 --> 01:16.030
that I did remember, and at least from seeing the 
students. All right, describe, you went to class

01:19.070 --> 01:22.610
on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. Describe that 
day. You got up at what time, came to campus, did

01:26.910 --> 01:30.590
what, and so forth. I usually would get up probably 
about, my class was usually about 8 o'clock. I'd

01:35.410 --> 01:37.930
try to get up as early as possible so we could get out 
by 12. I imagine we got up about a quarter to 7, got

01:38.610 --> 01:41.370
ready, and of course just lived in West Bryan and 
just take on Finnfeather. I could get to school in

01:46.290 --> 01:50.030
about 10, 15 minutes and park. Parking was not a big 
deal. Yeah, where did you park? I parked across

01:52.790 --> 01:59.670
from the drill field, that parking lot that still 
exists there. And

02:00.570 --> 02:08.330
walked the academic building, Nagel Hall, where 
most of my classes were. And then where would lunch

02:09.310 --> 02:11.010
be? Lunch would be back home probably because we 
would eat right before we went to work. And so my mom

02:16.750 --> 02:19.450
would have us some lunch, and then she'd give us a 
sack lunch for dinner where we would eat. But there

02:25.110 --> 02:29.810
was my brother, Moises, and I, and another friend 
named Mario, and they both would come back home to

02:30.750 --> 02:33.710
find lunch. And they worked to death to get the 
lunch and take the получить the lunch. So it was

02:38.110 --> 02:44.890
pretty much the same, the three of us pretty much 
had the same routine. So we'd see each other get in

02:44.870 --> 02:50.830
their cars, leaving or whatever, about the same 
time. I did start getting involved with school

02:50.810 --> 02:54.530
stuff later, but when I guess I started being able 
to work a little less. about a repeat of the fall in

03:00.560 --> 03:04.220
terms of the, you took. Another 12, 13 hours and, 
you know, I was always a full-time student and then

03:11.160 --> 03:14.600
I think two or three of my summers I ended up going to 
summer school. Right. Do you remember what your

03:16.987 --> 03:19.140
major was those first two semesters? My first 
semester it was history. Why? Because I had always

03:25.044 --> 03:26.660
liked history. I had thought of anthropology at 
some time but it never really gels. And then when

03:31.580 --> 03:35.720
political science department, I guess came, 
sprung from history, I guess it was, then I went

03:37.940 --> 03:40.100
into the political science. But I started with 
history. What did you think your career was going

03:41.140 --> 03:43.180
to be? What did you hope you were going to? Well, I 
had thought of being a lawyer at that time. Why?

03:49.626 --> 03:55.370
Well, I guess I began to get in my, to my courses. At 
that time the Hispanic, the Hispanic movement was

03:59.950 --> 04:02.730
beginning to get the notion of young Hispanics 
becoming lawyers or doctors and, you know, and

04:07.710 --> 04:10.490
promoting those professions became more and 
more. And I, I guess I began to see myself as someone

04:15.030 --> 04:18.550
who could become a lawyer and so that was, I mean, I 
started thinking about that but I thought about it

04:20.530 --> 04:22.051
more seriously obviously as I got. Was there a 
person that was a role model that you now realize

04:25.330 --> 04:29.510
somebody that, oh, he or she is a lawyer, I'd like to 
be? No, because quite frankly in Bryan there were

04:29.950 --> 04:37.920
no, I didn't know really any lawyers. I knew some of 
the judges here. My brothers and I started going to

04:42.660 --> 04:46.520
a prayer meeting early, early in the, when I was 
nine years old. But I didn't, we didn't know the men

04:49.020 --> 04:51.720
that personally but they were Judge Barron and 
some of the others who were Judge Davis, W.C.

04:53.960 --> 04:55.880
Davis. But no, I can't say that there was one person 
who

05:00.260 --> 05:06.310
inspired me to say you can be a lawyer or you ought to 
be a lawyer. I just wanted to achieve. I wanted to,

05:09.170 --> 05:13.290
to do the best I could and to be successful. How did 
you dress in those days as an Aggie freshman? Well,

05:19.210 --> 05:25.090
blue jeans and, and shirts, I mean, t-shirts or, 
not t-shirts but it was another, it had shirts

05:25.070 --> 05:29.090
with, I think it was blue jeans. Because we had some 
bell-bottom pants but they weren't that

05:32.620 --> 05:34.141
bell-bottom. But mainly blue jeans, you know, and 
shirt. Now were you clean-shaven then? I had,

05:44.300 --> 05:51.500
well I, yes, I had a mustache. And. As a freshman? 
No, my mustache came I think when I was like a

05:56.580 --> 05:58.041
sophomore or junior. I think that's when it began. 
And.

06:04.245 --> 06:07.640
Why I, I think my, I think my older brother started 
wearing a mustache and I thought, well I'll try

06:07.620 --> 06:09.420
one. But other than that, I mean, I, I didn't have a 
beard or anything. And your hair was what length?

06:15.060 --> 06:19.460
Oh, I would say it would, it would reach my 
shoulders. It wasn't, it wasn't long. I mean, it

06:20.560 --> 06:22.480
wasn't something that I had, I couldn't. But it 
was, it was very, very manageable. I mean,

06:25.980 --> 06:30.500
nowadays it would be considered relatively mild. 
The first year or two, what did you and your, your

06:32.980 --> 06:35.540
buddies do on a Saturday night to have fun? Where 
did y'all go play? Well, I guess we'd go to the

06:38.000 --> 06:42.910
movies downtown. We'd play, we'd go bowling. Go to 
pizza, get some pizza. Of course, we'd go to

06:49.800 --> 06:51.620
football games. There was always a, there was 
always those concerts before the football games

06:55.740 --> 06:57.161
that we went to. I

06:58.400 --> 07:04.770
can't say there was much, much more to do. Did. Was, 
was it normal for you and your buddies to go have

07:07.582 --> 07:13.130
beer somewhere? No, because, well, because we, I 
didn't drink. And, and the friends that we hung

07:15.190 --> 07:19.930
around with were basically non-drinkers also. So 
that never really was one of those, one of those

07:19.910 --> 07:26.860
traditions or activities we engaged in. It was 
really kind of. If you needed advice that first

07:30.120 --> 07:34.740
year, to whom did you turn other than a brother? No, 
no, no. Was there anybody on campus with whom you,

07:35.960 --> 07:40.040
that you turned to for, about what courses to take 
or? No, not that first year. Later there was a

07:46.070 --> 07:47.970
couple of people, but that. Who, who'd it be then, 
later? Was, Wayne Stark was probably one of the.

07:53.750 --> 07:55.031
How did you meet him? Well, my sophomore, latter 
second semester of my sophomore year, a friend of

07:55.570 --> 08:03.030
mine, who was a graduate student, we started 
talking about. Yeah. establishing a group on

08:07.513 --> 08:16.990
campus, a Hispanic group, and Wayne Stark had 
worked with a lot of the MSC groups, so we went to

08:16.970 --> 08:24.910
visit him and he was very, very supportive, very 
inspirational about achievement. He had worked

08:27.002 --> 08:32.230
with Henry Cisneros and Hector Gutierrez and a 
group of other students that he had sort of

08:32.210 --> 08:41.460
mentored and worked with and that's why he was a guy 
that could make you feel like, wow, I can

08:41.440 --> 08:45.487
accomplish something. And so I was very 
appreciative of Mr. Wayne Stark because he had

08:47.540 --> 08:55.740
this enthusiasm for making students feel good 
about themselves and really asking good

08:55.720 --> 09:02.320
questions about why and what do you mean by that and 
I mean, I mean. Not to challenge one, but to make you

09:02.643 --> 09:06.800
think critically. Now, you mentioned Hector and

09:06.780 --> 09:15.800
Henry, they were already gone, they had to 
graduate. Yes, right, they were a few years ahead,

09:15.780 --> 09:24.400
but I was aware of them through, I can't remember 
how, I guess just some different dialogue we had

09:24.380 --> 09:30.014
had and I met them later. I mean, when I was in 
college, I had met a couple of them. Did y'all

09:32.300 --> 09:33.741
organize a group? Yes, a group of us did and in fact 
it's called the Committee on the Awareness of the

09:33.720 --> 09:40.420
Mexican-American Culture. It's CAMOC, the 
Committee on the Awareness of the

09:42.091 --> 09:46.560
Mexican-American Culture. One of the things that 
my buddies and I began to see and these were

09:46.540 --> 09:51.800
students that were in the core, non-core, 
graduate students and undergrads. One of the

09:56.611 --> 09:58.120
things that we noticed that was that we felt that 
the reason why other students felt, you know, that

09:58.100 --> 10:02.480
they were somewhat,

10:02.460 --> 10:09.191
they saw us differently was because they didn't 
understand the culture. And so we thought, why not

10:11.020 --> 10:18.700
let's form a group that talks about the Hispanic 
culture, the Mexican-American culture, what it

10:18.680 --> 10:22.825
is, what it's not, and help in that vein. And the MSC 
became the sponsor group for that and so that's

10:25.260 --> 10:33.300
where I started getting involved with that 
activity. All right, now let's cover the whole

10:33.400 --> 10:38.662
four years from here on. Generalize about the 
Hispanic student body here. Where were they from,

10:44.371 --> 10:48.520
what was their background and so forth at A&M in 
those years? I think a lot of them came from San

10:49.526 --> 10:52.444
Antonio in the Valley. There's a good number from 
Houston. Laredo had always a large number, the

10:56.047 --> 11:00.780
Laredo hometown club, there was always a strong 
group. Yeah. And they were mainly boys because the

11:04.585 --> 11:10.790
girls were beginning to barely start coming in, 
but it wasn't really a stronghold there. I mean, I

11:12.664 --> 11:16.390
graduated in December of 73 so the girls hadn't 
really started coming in. The students came from

11:20.211 --> 11:23.730
families that were probably middle income or 
better. Were they first generation college

11:26.790 --> 11:29.736
students? Or some of them second? I would say they 
were. I think it was the second generation. A lot of

11:33.250 --> 11:37.590
them were second generation because their 
parents had gone to school somewhere else. I heard

11:38.130 --> 11:47.110
later, which I thought made sense, from Laredo, a 
lot of the Aggie mothers there had gone. There's

11:47.330 --> 11:49.490
kids that had gone to Laredo Community College. 
And once they got out, they sent their kids. And the

11:52.270 --> 12:02.030
mothers of these kids, they had gone to UT or had 
gone to some other school, but they sent their kids

11:52.270 --> 12:02.030
to A&M. And I don't know what that connection was 
from the very beginning, but a lot of

12:02.010 --> 12:09.210
Mexican-American kids. But there were also some 
of the kids who were very modest means. I mean, one

12:13.130 --> 12:19.390
of my best friends, Steven Salinas, who's an 
engineer, finished with a chemical engineering

12:13.130 --> 12:19.390
degree with a 4.0. And his brother finished here 
and went on to UT Medical Center. Both came from a

12:24.510 --> 12:30.230
home in West Laco, one-room house. And her mother 
was a nurse. And they worked. I mean, they were just

12:34.270 --> 12:35.611
poor. Now, did you all create KAMAK because you 
wanted to keep people from harassing you? Were you

12:44.830 --> 12:46.510
all being bothered? No, no. It wasn't harassment 
because it was never that physical. That's what I

12:52.150 --> 12:53.031
thought. But it was more of a sense of 
connectivity. In other words, a lot of this was

12:58.090 --> 13:02.350
driven by what a lot of the other kids were feeling. 
From Laredo and from the Valley. Because for them,

13:05.490 --> 13:08.670
coming to this environment was really, really 
tough. I was used to this environment. So, I mean,

13:10.790 --> 13:15.150
to me, it was not such an environment that I was not 
used to. I mean, being the only Hispanic in an

13:15.130 --> 13:18.990
all-white setting, that was not unusual. But this 
was a very interesting time, I guess, the career,

13:19.970 --> 13:26.050
the life of this state. In the late 60s, the 
Chicano, the so-called Hispanic Chicano

13:26.810 --> 13:32.150
movement was getting started. So, you would begin 
to hear and see literature that talked about this.

13:38.050 --> 13:41.910
Well, being 18, 19 years old, it was the kind of 
stuff that, okay, what is that all about? So, it

13:42.450 --> 13:46.690
awakened a lot of ideas about culture, language, 
history. Well, where is our history? Where is our

13:48.090 --> 13:48.751
background? Where do you see that? So, it began to 
raise a lot of those questions. So, it was one of

13:52.610 --> 13:56.030
those, the timing of it was just right. Had it 
happened five years before, that wouldn't have

13:56.510 --> 13:59.650
been the case. But it was a question of what was 
going on. What was going on in a larger external

14:02.330 --> 14:08.690
part of this state that impacted us? Were there 
some key professional staff and or faculty, other

14:09.170 --> 14:15.370
than Wayne Stark, that were positive in helping 
you all? Yeah. I think Chuck McCandless was one of

14:20.993 --> 14:23.970
them. He began to see the effort. Billy Lay, the 
director of admissions at that time. Mm-hmm.

14:32.041 --> 14:32.192
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm. And we had worked with him 
because we were trying to recruit students.

14:35.290 --> 14:35.551
Mm-hmm. I mean, we wanted to see how could we help 
create a positive feeling for Hispanic students.

14:43.290 --> 14:44.931
How could we help recruit students? So, we kind of 
on our own took that as an opportunity. We found

14:49.490 --> 14:54.630
ourselves to be somewhat privileged to be able to 
achieve what we were achieving going to college.

14:55.050 --> 14:57.670
And we wanted to see how do we bring more students 
in. I mean, it's some of the same thing that's

14:57.650 --> 15:02.810
happening now. But I haven't heard you infer in any 
way that this was intended to be some kind of

15:03.050 --> 15:09.250
protest. Oh, no. No, no. By no means. Because, I 
mean, I think we saw the A&M family being big enough

15:11.930 --> 15:19.530
to welcome people who were very different. And, by 
the way, at the same time, Hispanics and African

15:20.350 --> 15:23.610
Americans, we sort of connected because there 
were very few African American students on

15:23.850 --> 15:29.710
campus. And most of them were athletes. So, there 
was a... There was a connectivity there. And they

15:34.090 --> 15:35.011
felt alienated. They felt somewhat ostracized. 
Not that anybody would intentionally do

15:36.650 --> 15:41.690
something and say, get out of here, whatever. It 
was just there was not a social connection with a

15:42.210 --> 15:46.570
lot of the students. All right. In terms of 
vocabulary, in that era, normally, what did you

15:47.713 --> 15:55.510
and your associates, what wording did you all use 
to identify yourselves? As far as Latinos? Yeah,

16:01.870 --> 16:02.390
yeah. You weren't... You weren't Chicano. Well, 
no, there were Chicanos. No. Did you use that word

16:05.598 --> 16:06.990
very often? Yes, a lot of the students did. What was 
the preferable term? I think the word Chicano,

16:13.910 --> 16:21.210
Mexican-American, it depended on what part of the 
state you were from. No, I'm talking about here.

16:22.570 --> 16:28.310
What I'm saying, when people came to school here 
from other parts of the state, some came and they

16:28.290 --> 16:32.670
would say, don't ever call me Chicano because my 
parents, they don't like that word, They don't

16:32.950 --> 16:33.951
like the people from the Valley. Others, it was not 
such a bad... In San Antonio, there was not such a

16:35.650 --> 16:37.670
bad deal. It all depended on who it was and where 
they were from. What was the most widely accepted

16:45.450 --> 16:47.450
term? I said Chicano was because part of it was, 
again, there were groups that were getting

16:52.550 --> 16:55.170
started that would use the word Chicano. The word 
Chicano has always been part of our language, but

16:55.210 --> 17:00.510
it was used mainly among the groups. Here was, 
okay, let's surface. This group is a word that

17:03.170 --> 17:11.330
describes us as a group versus what the government 
has decided to call us, Mexican-American or

17:11.310 --> 17:14.070
whatever. It was more or less, we've decided who we 
are and we're going to use this term because it best

17:18.790 --> 17:20.191
describes us. In makeup, almost every single 
person in your group was Mexican-American, not

17:21.030 --> 17:29.790
from any other Latin background. No, it was being 
Mexican-American. Almost no Mexican nationals.

17:36.290 --> 17:41.370
No, because most of those would have been probably 
more associated with the international

17:41.350 --> 17:42.300
students. Okay. Let's see. Did I cut off a while 
ago, you said Chuck McCandless. Were there any

17:46.810 --> 17:52.530
other staff or faculty that were very helpful to 
you all during this time? Billy Lay, like I said. I

17:58.490 --> 18:01.170
think those were pretty much some of the... The 
ones that struck out the most. Did you have a

18:07.080 --> 18:08.860
sponsor? Did you have to have an advisor? Yes, and I 
don't remember who that was when it first started.

18:17.870 --> 18:19.690
I don't remember who that was exactly. Now, I'm 
assuming that in terms of religious affiliation,

18:22.190 --> 18:27.670
you would have been an exception as a Methodist. 
Yes, yes, because everybody else among the

18:28.930 --> 18:33.030
Hispanics were all Catholic. That's what I would 
have... But... There were some good number of

18:35.545 --> 18:37.970
Baptist students who came. Really? Yes. Okay. So 
there was a... In fact, my mother, at our home,

18:40.770 --> 18:47.510
every Sunday we would have... Ever since my 
brothers were in college, and even when I went, we

18:47.490 --> 18:52.360
would invite friends of ours to come eat lunch with 
us at my dad's house, at our house. And my mother

18:58.620 --> 19:04.260
would make caldo de res, you know, broth of beef. 
Mm-hmm. And some mole, chicken mole. And that was

19:08.080 --> 19:09.301
sort of our treat. And we would have maybe anywhere 
from five to ten college students that would come

19:09.960 --> 19:14.100
over and have... I've had guys that they were five, 
six, eight years old, and they'd say, Oh, I

19:21.830 --> 19:22.272
remember. I know who you are. I used to go to your 
house with your brothers all the time. So, I mean,

19:26.410 --> 19:30.150
I've had that happen to me even a couple of years 
ago. Let's see. Back in student. Life. Did you and

19:36.409 --> 19:40.560
your buddies get involved as undergraduates in 
any kind of good bull, or any pranks, any jokes?

19:45.020 --> 19:47.327
Well, no. It was really difficult to do, given the 
time that we had, limited time. I wouldn't want to

19:57.480 --> 20:06.140
say that I was all serious and no play, but

19:57.480 --> 20:06.140
we were... You have to understand, my parents had 
reared us pretty consistently. And so, doing some

20:08.700 --> 20:14.160
pranks was pretty much not one of those things we 
did.

20:17.420 --> 20:19.160
I really can't remember. In terms of going to 
class, what were your rules about going to class,

20:26.200 --> 20:30.680
and what kind of behavior did you try to follow in a 
class? I tried to attend every class. I was very...

20:35.470 --> 20:36.491
As much as possible. I guess my classes... One of 
the things that I began to really enjoy a lot were my

20:41.040 --> 20:49.740
sociology and philosophy classes. Doctor,

20:49.720 --> 21:02.880
he was a biologist,

20:49.720 --> 21:02.880
he taught a social biology course, older 
gentleman. And he opened my eyes to a lot of

21:02.860 --> 21:08.080
discussions about the effects of ecology, the 
effects of sociology and biology. And so, those

21:10.860 --> 21:13.880
classes were... Gary Halter was one of my 
professors. They

21:15.860 --> 21:25.880
opened my eyes a lot to the whole notion of who I was, 
who we were as a society. And again, politically

21:25.860 --> 21:31.880
speaking, things were changing in the state in 69 
to 73. I mean, there was a lot of Hispanic groups

21:31.860 --> 21:36.940
rising. There was a lot of issues about race 
issues, ethnic issues across the country. So,

21:41.920 --> 21:42.941
those were just really tough. Yeah. ¿How did you 
get to know each other? What was your family like?

21:45.920 --> 21:48.980
Can you take it? We were talking about key people. 
And you said Gary Halter... Doctor Van Riper, who

21:54.040 --> 21:56.980
at the time when I started... And I remember him as 
the department head in political science. He

22:00.960 --> 22:04.880
later on served as a reference for me to law school. 
So obviously he was quite... Did you have any

22:06.860 --> 22:08.880
courses with him? Yes. I took a graduate course 
with him in personnel management. I was, I took 12

22:15.960 --> 22:24.560
hours in grad school, though my heart was not in it 
because of circumstances that had changed for me.

22:25.540 --> 22:36.720
I,

22:25.540 --> 22:36.720
when I finished college, I got admitted to St. 
Mary's Law School, but because I didn't plan well

22:36.700 --> 22:44.860
enough, I was in love, my mind was a little 
confused, I decided to hold back. And, but as good

22:44.840 --> 22:53.290
fortune happens, I was offered a job as assistant 
director of admissions involving the

22:53.270 --> 22:56.070
recruitment of students. So all those things 
being what they were, I thought, you know, I'll put

22:56.050 --> 23:02.150
off law school for a while. It all, it bothered me a 
lot, and of course later on I did, eight years later

23:03.130 --> 23:07.550
I did go to law school, seven years later, but that 
was, that happened. All right, all right. And as

23:13.730 --> 23:14.751
you progressed? As you progressed through A&M, 
what, was there someone that became your advisor

23:14.730 --> 23:20.650
that you went to for advice and counsel?

23:26.630 --> 23:41.050
There was a gentleman by the name of,

23:26.630 --> 23:41.050
my brain is just going out on me here, he was a 
political science professor who happened to be a

23:41.030 --> 23:46.260
lawyer. Jack Woods? Jack Woods. Describe him. 
Jack Woods was a. He was a professor, I guess he was

23:52.100 --> 23:58.460
an adjunct professor perhaps, but he was a lawyer. 
And he was the first lawyer that I really got to know

23:58.440 --> 24:05.720
and talk, and he was, I took constitutional law 
under him and judicial process under him. And he

24:08.940 --> 24:15.620
really, really excited me about the law, and the 
class, the way he taught it. And he was a person that

24:15.600 --> 24:19.120
I could talk to, and we talked a lot about, about 
school. A couple of times I talked to him. He was a

24:20.100 --> 24:21.121
great teacher. Yeah. He invited me over to go to his 
house. In fact, he also served as a letter of

24:23.100 --> 24:28.920
reference for me. And I guess it, what it did, his 
relationship with me and my relationship to him,

24:28.900 --> 24:36.160
helped me with more ease and more comfort talk 
about, you know, what I wanted to do. It wasn't so

24:44.400 --> 24:50.080
much just a strictly uncomfortable discussion, 
but a very comfortable discussion about

24:50.060 --> 24:51.361
